.SH PreGLQ
Calculate the weights and nodes used in integrating a function by
Gauss\-Legendre quadrature.
.SH Usage
call PreGLQ (\f[CR]lower\f[R], \f[CR]upper\f[R], \f[CR]n\f[R],
\f[CR]zero\f[R], \f[CR]w\f[R], \f[CR]exitstatus\f[R])
.SH Parameters
.TP
\f[CR]lower\f[R] : input, real(dp)
The lower bound of the integration.
.TP
\f[CR]upper\f[R] : input, real(dp)
The upper bound of the integration.
.TP
\f[CR]n\f[R] : input, integer(int32)
The number of integration points to use.
This will integrate exactly a polynomial of degree \f[CR]2n\-1\f[R].
.TP
\f[CR]zero\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]n\f[R])
The zeros used in the Gauss\-Legendre quadrature.
.TP
\f[CR]w\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]n\f[R])
The weights used in the Gauss\-Legendre quadrature.
.TP
\f[CR]exitstatus\f[R] : output, optional, integer(int32)
If present, instead of executing a STOP when an error is encountered,
the variable exitstatus will be returned describing the error.
0 = No errors; 1 = Improper dimensions of input array; 2 = Improper
bounds for input variable; 3 = Error allocating memory; 4 = File IO
error.
.SH Description
\f[CR]PreGLQ\f[R] will calculate the weights and zeros used to integrate
a function using Gauss\-Legendre quadrature.
For \f[CR]n\f[R] quadrature points, the integration will be exact if the
function is a polynomial of degree \f[CR]2n\-1\f[R], or less.
The quadrature nodes correspond to the zeros of the Legendre polynomial
of degree \f[CR]n\f[R].
The number of quadrature points required to integrate a polynomial of
degree \f[CR]L\f[R] is \f[CR]ceiling((L+1)/2)\f[R].
.PP
To integrate a function between the bounds \f[CR]lower\f[R] and
\f[CR]upper\f[R] it is only necessary to calculate the sum of the
function evaluated at the nodes \f[CR]zero\f[R] multiplied by the
weights.
.PP
This is a slightly modified version of the algorithm that was published
in NUMERICAL RECIPES.
